===Etymology===
From {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|δῆμος||tr=dēmos|people|lang=grc}} + {{term|ὄνυμα||tr=onuma|name|lang=grc}}. Possibly coined or revived in 1997 by Paul Dickson of [[w:Merriam-Webster|Merriam-Webster]] in a manner similar to other "nyms".

{{confix|demo|onym}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈdɛmənɪm/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{rare}} A name for an [[inhabitant]] or [[native]] of a [[specific]] [[place]] that is derived from the [[name]] of the place.
#: ''Why is it that people from the United States use American as ''their'' '''demonym'''?''
# {{obsolete}} A [[pseudonym]] formed of an [[adjective]].
#: ''The Logophile has my favourite '''demonym''', I would write under it if he didn't.''

====Synonyms====
* [[gentilic]]

====Usage notes====
Although demonyms are capitalized in English, they are [[common noun]]s, not [[proper noun]]s.

